      "date": "2016-01-23 16:11:49.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nPlease review this patch.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "34376fa81434ca98149289c8b66408e3dfc0a6c8",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 577,
        "name": "Noopur Maheshwari",
        "email": "noopur.maheshwari@seagate.com",
        "username": "noopur.maheshwari",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2016-01-23 19:54:01.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nWith 2 MDTs (MDT0000 AND MDT0001), test_404/sanity-hsm deactivates the last MDT(MDT0001) in the list of export targets, that is - &target->ft_chain.\nfld_client_lookup() retries for another target, if the remote target is deactive. This was introduced in http://review.whamcloud.com/#/c/14313/\nWhile getting the next export target from the list using:\ntarget = list_entry(target->ft_chain.next, struct lu_fld_target,ft_chain);\n&(target->ft_chain) is the last entry in the list, and the next of the last entry(target->ft_chain.next) is the head of the list.\nNow, using the macro, ?list_entry?, maps the head of the list pointer back into a pointer to the structure that contains the list_head. Thus, it turns the head of the list into its containing structure(lu_fld_target). \nNow since the head of the list does not have any data associated with it, the containing structure(i.e. target) formed from the head of the list also does not have any data. Hence, an export target with no obd device data is generated.\nThis corrupted export target(generated from the head of the list) causes the assertion.\nThe fix is: While fld_client_lookup retries for another target,if the next entry in the export target list is the head of the list(&fld->lcf_targets), move to the next entry after\nthe head(target->ft_chain.next->next) and retrieve the target. Else retrieve the next target entry(target->ft_chain.next).",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
